81 - 276*(-0.00607) ≈ 0.881 + 1.675 ≈ 2.556 → a+b ≈ 0.426.  \n\nFrom eq1: 20a + 400*(-0.00607) + 20b = 5.126 → 20(a+b) - 2.428 = 5.126 → 20(a+b) = 7.554 → a+b = 0.3777. Slight inconsistency due to rounding in data; let’s solve exactly with more precision.\n\nActually, let’s do simpler: assume L(k²) = A + B*k² + C*(k²)².  \nUse L(20)=5.126, L(26)=6.007, L(32)=6.451.\n\nWrite system:  \nA + 20B + 400C = 5.126  … (1)  \nA + 26B + 676C = 6.007  … (2)  \nA + 32B + 1024C = 6.451 … (3)  \n\n(2)-(1): 6B + 276C = 0.881  … (4)  \n(3)-(2): 6B + 348C = 0.444  … (5)  \n\n(5)-(4): 72C = -0.437 → C ≈ -0.00606944.  \n\nFrom (4): 6B = 0.881 - 276*(-0.00606944) = 0.881 + 1.67516 = 2.55616 → B ≈ 0.426027.  \n\nFrom (1): A = 5.126 - 20*0.426027 - 400*(-0.00606944)  \n= 5.126 - 8.52054 + 2.42778 = -0.96676.\n\nSo L(k²) ≈ -0.9668 + 0.4260*k² - 0.006069*(k²)².\n\nFor k² = 40:  \nL(40) ≈ -0.9668 + 0.4260*40 - 0.006069*1600  \n= -0.9668 + 17.04 - 9.7104 = 6.3628.\n\nThat gives R ≈ 10^6.3628 ≈ **2.30 × 10⁶**.\n\nThis is **much smaller** than Tsuchimura’s 1.17×10⁹. Why? Because the quadratic fit to last 3 exact points suggests strong saturation — but we know k²=36 upper bound is 8×10⁷, so L(36) ≤ 7.903. Our quadratic predicts L(36) ≈ -0.9668 + 15.336 - 7.864 = 6.5052 (only 3.2×10⁶), which is **below** the known upper bound 8×10⁷. So quadratic in k² for L(k²) might be too strong a deceleration.\n\n---\n\n### **2.2 Fit in log(R) vs p(k)**\n\nTsuchimura’s model: log_e(R) ≈ 1.160 × p(k).  \np(k) for k²=32 is 14 → log_e(R)≈16.24, true log_e(R)=log(2.823e6)≈14.85 (error ~8.5%).  \nFor k²=20, p=9 → predicted log_e=10.44, actual log_e(133679)=11.80 (error ~13%).  \nSo the 1.160 factor is an average over early points; later points fall below the line.\n\nLet’s check actual log_e(R) / p(k):\n\n| k² | p(k) | log_e(R) | ratio |\n|----|------|----------|-------|\n| 20 | 9    | 11.80    | 1.311 |\n| 26 | 12   | 13.83    | 1.1525|\n| 32 | 14   | 14.85    | 1.0607|\n\nTrend: ratio is decreasing toward 1.0 maybe.\n\nIf ratio for k²=40 is ~1.0, then log_e(R) ≈ p(40)=18 → R ≈ e¹⁸ ≈ 6.57×10⁷.  \nIf ratio continues linear drop from k²=20,26,32:  \nratios: 1.311, 1.1525, 1.0607. Δp=3 each time, Δratio≈-0.158, -0.0918. Next Δp=3 to p=17 (k²=36? Wait p(36)=16, p(40)=18). Let’s interpolate:\n\nAt p=14, ratio=1.0607.  \nAt p=12, ratio=1.1525.  \nSo from p=12 to 14, Δratio=-0.0918 over Δp=2 → slope m≈-0.0459 per p unit.\n\nExtrapolate to p=18: from p=14, Δp=4 → Δratio≈-0.1836 → ratio≈1.0607-0.1836=0.8771.\n\nThen log_e(R) ≈ 0.8771×18 = 15.788 → R ≈ e¹⁵·⁷⁹ ≈ 7.2×10⁶.\n\nSo this gives order 10⁷.\n\n---\n\n### **2.3 Upper bound constraints**\n\nWe know:  \nk²=36 → R < 8.00×10⁷.  \nk²=34 → R < 2.43×10⁷.\n\nIf R_moat(k²) is increasing with k² (must be, since larger step size can reach farther), then:  \nR_moat(40) > R_moat(36) (unknown exact, but at least > some lower bound).  \nBut we only have upper bounds for 34,36, not exact R.\n\nIf the exact R for 36 is close to its upper bound 8×10⁷, then R for 40 could be larger but maybe not massively larger if growth is slowing.\n\n---\n\n## **3. Theoretical considerations**\n\n### **3.1 Percolation analogy**\n\nIn continuum percolation with disks radius r, critical density η_c ≈ 1.128 (for Poisson process in 2D).  \nGaussian primes density at norm N is ~ 1/(2 log N) in first octant, but in full plane it’s ~ 1/(log N) per area? Actually: #Gaussian primes with norm² ≤ X ~ X/log X (up to constant).  \nSo areal density at radius R is ~ (1/(πR²)) × (πR²/log R²) = 1/(2 log R) (points per unit area? Wait, that’s not right — careful).\n\nNumber in disk radius R ≈ R²/log R. Area = πR², so density = (R²/log R)/(πR²) = 1/(π log R). Yes, density → 0 as R→∞, but slowly.\n\nPercation threshold in 2D Poisson Boolean model: λ_c ≈ 1.128. λ = mean number of points per area of πr². Here λ = (density) × πr² = (1/(π log R)) × πr² = r² / log R.\n\nFor percolation, need λ > λ_c for infinite cluster. Here r=k fixed, R increasing → λ decreases as 1/log R, so eventually λ < λ_c → no percolation. This is why moats exist for any fixed k.\n\nBut here we ask: given k, how far can we go before λ drops below λ_c locally? That’s not exactly right — we only need connectivity to origin, not infinite cluster globally.\n\nBetter: think of branching process. Each prime has expected number of neighbors within distance k ≈ density × πk² = (πk²)/(π log R) = k²/log R. For branching to survive, need k²/log R > 1 (mean children > 1). So critical R satisfies log R ≈ k².\n\nFor k²=40 → log R ≈ 40 → R ≈ e⁴⁰ ≈ 2.35×10¹⁷ — huge! But we observe R_moat(36) < 10⁸. So mean children > 1 condition is too weak — clustering matters, and finite-size effects kill the component earlier.\n\n---\n\n### **3.2 Origin-lineage extinction mechanism**\n\nThe component dies not because density is too low everywhere, but because **forward growth** (primes with larger norm) have fewer connections back to the cluster. At each step, new primes are found, but they might not connect to any prime in the current cluster — they form separate islands. The existing cluster stops growing when all frontier primes have no neighbors ahead within step k.\n\nThis depends on **local gaps** in prime distribution at scale ~k. Gaussian primes are distributed like primes p=4m+1 (points on circle) and p=4m+3 (on axes). The p=4m+1 ones are more relevant off-axis. Their average spacing at norm N is ~ log N. If k < log R, then gaps larger than k become likely, causing disconnection.\n\nFor R ~ 10⁸, log R ~ 18.4, k=6, so k < log R indeed. So isolated islands form.\n\n---\n\n## **4. Synthesis prediction**\n\nGiven:  \n- Tsuchimura’s formula predicts ~1.17×10⁹.  \n- Empirical extrapolation of exact data (k²≤32) suggests saturation ~10⁷.  \n- Upper bound for k²=36 is 8×10⁷.  \n- Growth rate log₁₀(R) per k² unit dropped from 0.147 (20→26) to 0.074 (26→32). If it halves again to ~0.037 for 32→40, then Δlog₁₀(R) ≈ 0.037×8 = 0.296, so log₁₀(R_40) ≈ 6.451 + 0.296 = 6.747 → R ≈ 5.6×10⁶.\n\nBut that’s below the k²=36 upper bound, so impossible since R_moat(40) > R_moat(36).  \n\nSo maybe growth rate doesn’t halve again; maybe it stabilizes ~0.05 per k² unit. Then Δlog₁₀ ≈ 0.4 → log₁₀ ≈ 6.85 → R ≈ 7×10⁶.\n\nBut given k²=36 bound is 8×10⁷, maybe R_moat(36) is around 5×10⁷, and 40 is 1.5–2× that → 7.5×10⁷ to 1×10⁸.\n\n---\n\n**Thus, my independent prediction:**\n\n- **Best estimate**: R_moat(40) ≈ 6×10⁷ to 2×10⁸.  \n- **Confidence interval**: 3×10⁷ to 5×10⁸ (wide due to extrapolation uncertainty).  \n- **Median guess**: ~1.2×10⁸.\n\nThis is **two orders of magnitude below** Tsuchimura’s 1.17×10⁹, because the per-p(k) ratio has been falling.\n\n---\n\n## **5. Computational search strategy**\n\nStart probing at norm ~5×10⁷ (below k²=36 upper bound) and move outward in bands of width ~k. Use Tsuchimura’s band method: maintain only frontier within distance k of current farthest reachable point. Primality testing will be the bottleneck; use Miller–Rabin with enough bases for deterministic range up to ~10⁹. Parallelize sieve by norm intervals across CPUs.\n\nGiven the predicted R ~10⁸, the search space is large but feasible with distributed computing (similar scale to k²=36 search which went to 8×10⁷ bound in 26 hours on 38 CPUs). Expect k²=40 search to take ~2–3 times longer if R is ~1.2×10⁸.\n\n---\n\n**Final answer:**  \nPredicted R_moat(40) ≈ **1.2 × 10⁸**, with uncertainty spanning roughly [3×10⁷, 5×10⁸].  \nThe mechanism is likely **origin-lineage extinction** due to local gaps in Gaussian primes at scale k, occurring well before density drops below percolation threshold globally.","refusal":null,"reasoning":null}}],"usage":{"prompt_tokens":2533,"completion_tokens":3598,"total_tokens":6131,"cost":0.00428191,"is_byok":false,"prompt_tokens_details":{"cached_tokens":0,"cache_write_tokens":0,"audio_tokens":0,"video_tokens":0},"cost_details":{"upstream_inference_cost":0.00428191,"upstream_inference_prompt_cost":0.00068391,"upstream_inference_completions_cost":0.003598},"com